description.text:
I purchased a set of LED sewing machines work lights to brighten up my build platform, but they have a magnetic mount. Of course, my printer frame is Lexan, so no real good places to mount them. I did have a simpler 'hanger' mount for them, but after converting my printer first to a RAMPS setup, and then to a dual Bowden setup, I needed to make a more permanent solution.

These mounts bolt in place using the original mounting holes for the display that came with the printer. Since I don't use that display anymore, it doesn't matter that the button holes get covered. I also use the mounting holes to mount my cold ends on the backside of the cross piece.

It would be fairly easy to modify them to allow access the display and buttons if you are still using the original control board.

The lamps themselves simply push into the mounts and stay put via friction. They do not seem to want to work themselves out, but you could add a small drop of glue if you felt it was needed.

These are the lamps I purchased:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0177KS714/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I printed in PLA with 45 or 50 percent infill, but it could probably do with less.

title: Large RAMPS Case for ANET A8

description.text:
When converting my printer to a RAMPS setup, I tried several methods of mounting and enclosing the control boards. I remixed the original to be quite a bit larger, and to use a separate mount plate.

The mounting plate allows me to run wires down behind the case.

The larger size allows more room for routing cables inside the box (also more room for my fat fingers...)

It also gives me plenty of room for expander boards down the line.

I modified the cooling vents to provide more positive pressure on the inside of the case before forcing the air out the side. I feel this allows the air to flow better inside the box across the boards and heat sinks.

I also removed the need for nuts on the inside. I am using hardware I have on hand, so my screws thread directly into the holes.

BEWARE!!
This configuration mounts the case quite low on the printer. You could be short on wire coming from your extruders, etc. and it does not leave much room on the bottom for plugging in your USB cable.
You may want to modify the mount to sit the case higher.
ALSO... there is only about 7mm of space between the case and the X stepper. Be careful how you route your wires on that side.

ANET A8

This mount and case are both quite large. You may want to use rafts if you have adhesion issues.

Also, slight trimming / cleanup of pieces to ensure clean fit up of parts.

This is a suction hood for my Stepcraft 2/600 mill with a Kress 800kfme.

You will need

  • 1x M5 Nut

Update 05.09.2016:

  • Modified the brush part in order to be able to use a strip brush (I was defenitely not good in glueing in the brush)
  • Added a clamping part for the strip brush. This part is very tight in order to hold the brush in place. I ordered this brush: http://www.enobi.de/waermedaemmung/buerstendichtung/mi0003 With 30mm brush hairs.

I also added some holder for the cable of the KRESS mill to the suction hose (mine is ID/OD 25/28mm) and also holders for the 40mm tubes which are installed in my housing.

description.text:
My Printrbot LC v1 has a storied history, including printing its own repair parts when it arrived from the eBay seller (in a nearly empty cardboard box) in less than intact condition.

This corrects the last long-standing problem with it, that its right foot was completely shattered and unusable to prop the printer up.

Since these leave the printer sitting a few millimeters higher than the stock feet, I recommend printing two pairs, and replacing both sides to keep the printer level.

These are also merely press-fit. While they fit snugly enough that I don't expect them to fall off in normal usage, you may want to keep this in mind if you lift your printer off of the table often.

Created at 2am using OpenSCAD, sliced with Slic3r, and printed using OctoPrint.

This is an easy item for balancing the neck strap of my Turnigy 9X transmitter. It level the gravity point to allow you to focus in moving the sticks instead of holding the remote.  
This is my first design after some time working with my Prusa Air V2.

Download the STL file, put in your favourite printing software and print. Once printed you should use some bolt and nut to hold to your transmitter. I have used 2 x grower washer for fixing the position of the piece in the transmitter. The small hole is used to put your neck strap.  
If you want to customize or open the Blender source file you will find two visible objects. Peça01 (item01 is the translation in English) is the printable item. Anella01 is the auxiliary item from the transmitter to calculate the dimensions of the item.

title: Prusa Original i3 Mk2 Cable Chains

description.text:
NOTE: This is for the MK2 and NOT the MK2S. If you have the MK2S you will need a different top part. User kraq has created this one to make it compatible:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2445193

Thanks, kraq!

I really like the improvements made to the Mk2 of the Prusa Original i3. All in all, it's a very good product. I like to use cable chains instead of cable wraps, so these are my modifications to add them to the Mk2.

The Mk2 uses every bit of space available for the heatbed which proved a bit difficult for adding the cable chain with proper clearance. To make up for this, I added a couple of additional parts to allow the part connecting to the x carriage rotate about the z axis. My other goal was to make as minimal modifications as possible. The only parts from the kit I've replaced are the Rambo housing and heatbed cable cover. Also included in the files are a cable chain that will allow full rotation, not only in one direction. This is to be used at the end of the chain (the links nearest the x carriage and nearest the heatbed cover).

Please note: With this you will no longer be able to use the spool holder. You will need to mount it elsewhere.

You will need to measure your cable lengths. After printing 20 links (or so) you should be able to connect them and figure out how many total you will need. Based on multiple reports, people have different cable lengths on their Mk2s. Also, at some point the rambo box changed where you may need to print a new cover as well.

I printed 32 regular links + 1 full rotation link for the long chain to the extruder and 16 regular links + 1 full rotation link to the heat bed. To install the top part on the x axis carriage, remove the zip tie around the cables. This piece should fit onto the carriage. You can then reinstall a new zip tie going through the new part as well its the original path. An additional zip tie to hold the cables in place just before they enter the chain is recommended.

title: Flashforge Creator Pro 2016 Filament Holder Upgrade

description.text:
This is an add-on upgrade to the Flashforge Creator Pro 2016 model.
I recommend that this is the first thing that you print when unboxing your Flashforge Creator Pro 2016 because the original filament feed design is not very good.
This bracket resolved the issue that I experienced where the filament would coil off of my filament roll and would get stuck between the roll and the printer housing, causing it to stop feeding into the extruder.

Assembly steps (also see attached photos for install):

  1. Print upright without raft/supports using print settings described below for ABS.
  2. Click this bracket into the same holders as the Creator Pro filament guide tubes on the back of the case.
  3. Insert the filament guide tubes into the top hole of the bracket.
  4. Feed your filament through the small hole in the bottom of the bracket and into the filament guide tube and load the filament as normal.

P.S. If you're annoyed that I cut the name "BJ Dizza" into the part and don't know how to remove it, let me know and I will upload a new version without the name (or another name if you want).

Printer:

Flashforge Creator Pro 2016

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm layer height

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I used the following print settings with the ReplicatorG slicing software:
Object infill - 20%;
Layer Height - 0.2 mm;
Number of shells - 1;
Feedrate - 60 mm/s;
Travel feedrate - 80;
Print temperature - 230 degC;

Print orientation - Print in an orientation so that the text is upright. Refer to the attached screenshot.

I based this design off of a similar bracket that was made for a previous version of the Creator Pro.
The 2016 model has a wider spacing between the filament guide tube holders and this was the main reason for creating my own.
I optimised the height so that it would fit into two of the clips that would normally hold the filament guide tube.
I also added a section so that the filament guide tubes would sit nicely in the bracket without falling through.

description.text:
Various cases for the $9.00US C.H.I.P. computer. They are as precise as I could make them where they still reliably print and fit. The cases should be compatible with almost any USB cable. The cutout for the A/V jack may need to be enlarged if you don't have a low profile cable. The post for the power/reset switch should prevent accidental damage if you're trying to poke it with a paperclip. Depending on your material and print settings, you can also press on the center of the lid near the switch to activate it.

The versions with battery in the name provide a cavity 31.8mm wide, 65.8mm long, and 12.5mm high. If your battery is long you lose a bit of width (2.8mm) near the mounting screw on the C.H.I.P. You may also lose 3mm of height due to the parts on the bottom of the C.H.I.P.

I'm working on a modified design that will be more flexible in terms of battery sizes, mounting options, and so on.

description.text:
Print a few of these to bring along on your next flight. You never know when maintenance might overlook a missing bolt. The pilot will appreciate your ingenuity when you offer to tighten up the plane with one of these.

OEM bolts are threaded, but not to worry. Thanks to the miracle of soft plastic, this bolt is self-threading. Just drive it home with a #3 Phillips screwdriver until the head is flush with the wing. Existing threads in the aluminum will cut perfect threads into the bolt and provide plenty of gripping power. Thanks to frankvdh for this tip!

Here is a discussion of aircraft fasteners.

Wing photo credit to boldmethod.com.

Happy trip!

title: Ultimaker 2 Raspberry Pi and relay support

description.text:
This is a support for a Raspberry Pi (B+, 2, 3) and a relay for the Ultimaker 2.

The idea is to install OctoPi on the Raspberry Pi and control the 3D printer remotely. The power to the printer can be turned on and off remotely (instead of having to toggle the button behind the printer), so the Ultimaker extruder fan does not work all the time. This part will hold the Raspberry Pi and relay under the printer, hidden from view.

The support is full of holes in order save plastic and avoid it curling up on the edges.

The printer will remain usable just like before and should not void the warranty (unless you mess up something).

Parts list

  • 3D printed support
  • Raspberry Pi
  • Micro-SD card for the RPi
  • Relay
  • M2.5 x 5 screws (x4)
  • M3 x 5 screws (x4)
  • M3 x 10 screws (x3)
  • Wire
  • Prototyping cables/jumper wires (x3)

Instructions

  • Disconnect power from Ultimaker
  • Install OctoPi, follow these instructions
  • Open the Ultimaker electronics box under the printer by unscrewing two bolts
  • Solder wires on the Ultimaker 2 board as shown on the pictures
  • Connect the relay and the Raspberry Pi with prototyping cables as shown on the pictures, the signal wire goes on the GPIO 18 of the RPi
  • Connect the wires to the relay between the center and the NO terminals (NO = normally open)
  • Reassemble everything
  • Connect power on the Ultimaker (do not turn on via the button)
  • Power on the Raspberry Pi (follow the usage instructions if it's your first time)
  • Follow these instructions to add the options to control the relay from OctoPi

Ultimaker 2 electronics box, held in place with 2 bolts. You can see the 3 holes under the box where the 3D printed part will be attached 3D printed part to hold the Raspberry Pi and the relay Raspberry Pi 3 and relay attached on the 3D printed part and connected via prototyping cables Wire soldered in parallel with the Ultimaker toggle button (on position) All elements mounted on the Ultimaker 2 Closed electronics box with the wires going to the relay (NO position) Closer look New options to turn the 3D printer on and off from OctoPrint installed on the RPi

title: The GO Case: A Pokedex Aimer Phone Case!

description.text:
WATCH THE VIDEO HERE : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T-W2mUFAqX0

Check out our Etsy for all of our 3D printed awesomeness!
https://www.etsy.com/shop/CarryTheWhat

Since uploading the original video on Instagram on August 2nd, we've received thousands of messages asking us to release the design! We love Open Source projects, so we naturally wanted to release our original model! The only problem was, it turned out there were a LOT of different phone types! Like, a LOT.

"...i have a bq aquaris E5 , and i am really interested too (i am of spain)"

"...please make one for Galaxy J5 please thx"

"...make for Sony Xperia m4 aqua please"

We decided the best (and most efficient!) way to address this was to create a brand new parametric model, one that could be remixed easily to create any kind of phone case with just a few tweaks! Using Thingiverse's Customizer, you can input your phone's dimensions and features, and the case will print perfect just for you!

This is still a Work-In-Progress, so we expect to be patching bugs and adding features over the coming days and weeks. This is also our first time using Customizer on such a large scale, so let us know if you run into any problems generating a case for your phone type!

We're thrilled and humbled by the community response to this model, and want to thank everyone who wanted to download a copy! We can't wait to see all the Makes and Remixes of our design!

-- 3D Central

We've included the .STL of the model used in the original video (with the painted buttons), which is made for an iPhone 5S. This version has not been made for any other phone, and was only made as a single prototype. We're still releasing it for download in case anyone wants to remix or adapt it for any other phones! It's a remix of the awesome design by ChrisIntravaia; be sure to check it out!

Using Customizer, input your phone's dimensions in millimeters, including length, width, depth, camera window placement and spacing, etc.

Customizer opens with the dimensions/camera placement of an iPhone 6 already populated.

Once you have measured your phone and populated all the fields, click 'CREATE THING' to create a new derivative, which will be custom made for your phone! This will automatically generate all the .stl files you need to print!

To print, make sure you download the following .stl files for your case:

CaseTop.stl
CaseBottom.stl
CaseLid.stl
AimerHinge.stl

You also need these files, which are the same for every phone type:

Button.stl
Hinge.stl (x2)
LockPin.stl

Common phones have already been included, and new ones will be added as they are generated!

We've included several premade models under the 'Thing Files' tab. You can find several common phone types there, including:

iPhone 5
iPhone 6
iPhone 6 Plus
Samsung Galaxy Note 5

The following files are custom for each phone type:

CaseTop.stl
CaseBottom.stl
CaseLid.stl
AimerHinge.stl

The following files are generic, and are used for every phone type:

Button.stl
Hinge.stl (x2)
LockPin.stl

We'll be adding to these models as we expand our collection!

ASSEMBLY VIDEO COMING SOON!

To assemble the GO Case, print the lid and aimer both flat.

The case pieces both print upright, and are made to simply snap together! This friction fit joint works well with ABS filament, but may not work as well with PLA. For a firm connection, you can use a hammer on the edges to join the two pieces. You can also add a little glue if you want it to really be super snug.

The hinges are a print-in-place model (use ABS filament for the hinge, PLA seems to work poorly for pins in our experience), and can be printed in one piece! The button latch slides down and acts as a lock, to keep the lid securely shut when the case is in your backpack or pocket! Place the Lock Pin, long side down, in the insert in the Case Top, and glue the Button to the protruding piece of the Lock Pin.

Once everything is printed, glue some 1/4" x 1/16" magnets into the voids in the case, which will allow it to snap shut when closed. Some super glue in the hole will keep the magnets securely in place.

Snap the hinges into the lid and the combined case pieces, and snap the aimer into the case. That's it! Now you're ready to GO!

title: X Carriage for Prusa Mendel and boltable bushings

description.text:
This uses the boltable PLA bushings from Aleph Objects and takes a groovemount extruder/hotend. The extruder sits on a raised mounting area so that it can overlap the bushing mount screws, resulting in a carriage that is both smaller and stiffer.
Includes a belt tightener with ram (ram borrowed from Triffid Hunter). There's code in the SCAD for a preliminary fan mount which has been mangled by me from an original by Greg Frost I think. I had to beat on it because I had to print this right side up to get the raised area. I will update this later when I finish with the fan mount.

Bushings to go with this are here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10647 Mount with raised circle up. Bushings bolt on the bottom, belt clamps on top. The belt tightener goes open end down right on top of the carriage, the belt loops around behind and up to the top where it is clamped. Use a nut and screw along with the ram in the tightener. Photo is of a previous revision, but shows how the belt goes on.

title: Mitsubishi Lancer Heater Control Knob Shaft

description.text:
This is a control shaft for the hot-cold knob on a 2004-2006 Mitsubishi Lancer. It should fit most similar models.

This part commonly breaks due to a design flaw that makes it difficult to turn.
A recall supposedly fixes the problem... but it does not.

This part is placed vertically because the shaft walls would not print well, but this creates a shear effect along the layers. If your printer can do it, I recommend placing it horizontal to remove the shear effect.

This was made with tinkercad, https://tinkercad.com/things/2IbqGGgu56P

Edit: It turns out Ebay is now selling these for $25. When this first broke for me, I could only order the whole unit for $400, hence the necessity of the work.

title: Better Cooler Drain Plug (RubberMaid Cooler) with o-rings.
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I lost the plug for this darn cooler long ago, in a galaxy far far away. Since then I've made several plug replacements. I even made one out of duct tape! This time I decided to finally make the plug to end all plugs and design and 3d print one. So this is my latest iteration. I'm confident to declare that you can not buy a better plug for your cooler than this. It's better designed and better made than the plug that came with the cooler and it's also better than the replacement plugs you can buy.

The hole on my cooler is right at 9.7 mm at the hole. I'm pretty sure this will fit quite a few coolers from different makers. But I've included my design files so you can adjust it for your needs.

I made this with grooves in it to put two rubber o-rings on to ensure a water tight seal. I got an assortment set of o-rings on AliExpress just for these types of projects. So the o-ring that I intend to use for this is labeled 9 x 2 mm.

I also filleted all the edges, which is trivial in FreeCad. Which is the primary reason I use it. I mean other than it being FREE, and it runs on Linux.

UPDATES
I have printed this object a couple of times now. I printed it on a PrintrBot Simple Metal, and it works, but you will want supports, and a brim. It took about an hour at highest resolution. Then I printed it on a Zortrax and it printed at high resolution in only 33 minutes. So I decided I'm having an affair with the Zortrax printer now. The slots for the o-rings in the model ended up being a touch too shallow. So I've made them 0.4mm deeper and I'm printing the updated plug now. But without the o-rings the plug fits quite snugly. I may want to make the handle bigger to make it easier to put on and pull off.

The files are now on revision 3.

Update
I printed rev 3, and it was too tight initially. However I put a little vaseline on the o-rings and they slid in perfectly tight. Now I'm pretty sure vaseline is NOT the appropriate thing to put on o-rings (and I think mine are nitrile o-rings). But I was in a hurry and wanted to see if all it needed was a little lubricant. And that was the ticket. Now I'm pretty sure the thing I should have used should have been silicone grease. Which I have in my tackle box for my fishing reels.

UPDATE

I've decided that even with the lubrication it's still just a touch too tight. So I've redesigning the slots for the o-rings to be a little bit deeper. I've increased the size of the base so it's easier to grab with my big hands. I'm reprinting it soon. So this latest version is Rev 4. Rev 3 worked and I will keep it as a backup plug. But Rev 4 is the gold standard for now.

Latest Revision is Rev 4.

I've printed and tested Rev 4 on a printrbot and a Zortrax at high resolution, out of ABS. It fits like a dream. First I coated the o-rings with the proper silicone grease. It only takes a smidge. Then when inserting it into the drain hole, it resists at first, then snaps right in all the way in. I have yet to fill the cooler with water to test for water tightness, but I'm pretty confident its going to work perfectly. Actually this plug is better constructed than the original that came with the cooler and the replacements that they sell online.

I field tested the Rev 4 this weekend and it didn't leak ONE drop. So I consider this a huge success and I can finally put this project to rest.

I took the cooler on a 3 day fishing trip last weekend, and not one drop did it leak. The bottom of the cooler was a dry as a bone. I printed a second one to duck tape to the inside of the lid as a backup.

description.text: Square Halbach magnet designed specifically for the BY088-N52 magnets from K&J Magnetics (http://www.kjmagnetics.com/). To be used for testing NMR without requiring a superconducting magnet. Hall probe measurements agreed well with simulation.

Notes:

Printed using PETG, as it's both readily available and holds up better in liquid nitrogen environments than PLA or ABS.

Assembly

Be extremely careful if you try to assemble these magnets. They are very strong, and you'll be putting them into a position they don't want to be in. Expect them to fly out when you join two pieces together. Install the center plate before putting two pieces together, and don't remove until all three pieces are in place (but not fully tightened). Arrows have been incorporated into the print, indicating which way north should be aligned. When assembling the stack, make sure all layers are aligned identically with the layer below.

Exercise extreme caution, and wear safety glasses.

comments.author: ycosy

comments.text: Quite likely, although with Halbachs you're limited by the small size of the center hole. In general, smaller hole -> larger field (although it's a bit more of a complicated relationship between both the radius of the hole and the outer radius of the entire magnet). Also given the transverse nature of this field, if you wanted a more impressive Lorentz effect you could make a small rail gun with it so that the current would flow transverse to the height of the magnet, causing the force to point out of the top.
